SYMPTOM_TEXT: skin is on fire after second dose; swelling in her soft palate after second dose; angioedema after 2nd dose; Ribs were swollen after 2nd dose; tongue was swollen//2nd dose; Covered in hives after 2nd dose; small reaction// 1st dose; A spontaneous report was received from a healthcare facility staff member concerning a 36-year female patient who developed urticaria, angioedema, swollen ribs, swollen tongue, hives that were welts, skin burning and soft palate swelling.    The patient's medical history was not provided.  Concomitant product use was not provided/unknown by the reporter.   The patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 025L20A) on 14-JAN-2021 intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.    After the patient's first injection on 14-Jan-2021 the patient developed a small reaction within 45 minutes.  The patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 006M20A) on 11-FEB-2021 intramuscularly in the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   After the receiving their second injection on 11-FEB-2021 the patient went to the ER on 12Feb2021. The patient developed angioedema and an epinephrine pen was used.  The patient also had swollen ribs, a swollen tongue and hives and was given a steroid shot. The patient then returned to the ER on 14Feb2021 for angioedema. The patient was given intravenous Diphenhydramine, intravenous dexamethasone and intravenous Famotidine. The patient developed hives that became welts, that were bright red in color and burned. The patient described that their skin felt like it was on fire, and there was swelling in their soft palate.    The outcome of the events were unknown/not reported.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 36 year old, female patient, who experienced a serious unexpected event of Angioedema, and a few non-serious events, after receiving second dose mRNA-1273 (Lot# 006M20A).  Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Further information has been requested.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: No adverse event (no reported medical history)

Started feeling unwell; Headaches; Body aches; Chest pain; Didn't had wishes to eat; Diarrhea; COVID-19 pneumonia; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 69-year-old male patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced COVID-19 pneumonia, feeling unwell, headaches, body aches, chest pain, decreased appetite and diarrhea  The patient's medical history high blood pressure which was controlled with medication. Concomitant product use included nifedipine and fenofibrate.  On 20-JAN-2021, approximately a week and a half or two prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number 030L20A) intramuscularly in the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  A week and a half or two later the patient stated feeling unwell, headaches, body aches, chest pain, decreased appetite and diarrhea for which patient was hospitalized on 06-FEB-2021. Since everything seemed to be fine the patient was discharged on an unknown date in FEB-2021 however, patient's family was not notified that it was a late reaction to the vaccine's first dose. Later, due to shortness of breath he was hospitalized again on 08-FEB-2021 and was diagnosed for pneumonia and was intubated on the same day. Due to COVID-19 situation patient's family could not be in the facilities and that there wasn't any follow up of the patient given to the family, so family did not have much information.  During the first hospitalization(06-FEB-2021) the patient had a blood test which showed a normal result and was tested for COVID-19 and Influenza, both were negative. During second hospitalization (08-FEB-2021) the hospital said that the patient was stable. The patient's family did not know the results of the tests conducted at the time.   The action taken with the vaccine in response to the events is not applicable.  The outcome of COVID-19 pneumonia was fatal. The patient died on 14 Feb 2021  The cause of death was reported as COVID-19 related pneumonia. The autopsy was not done.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding this event has been provided at this time.  The cause of death was reported as COVID-19 related pneumonia. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Completely out/eyes were closed; looked like he wasn't breathing; Began to shake, patient's head and arm shocked; Weak; little confused; A spontaneous report  was received from a consumer concerning a 69 years-old male patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced began to shake (MedDRA PT: tremor), head and arm shocked (MedDRA PT: tremor), completely out/eyes were closed (MedDRA PT: loss of consciousness), looked like he wasn't breathing (MedDRA PT: respiratory arrest), weak (MedDRA PT: asthenia), and little confused (MedDRA PT: confusional state).  The patient's medical history included stroke. Concomitant product use included unspecified blood pressure pills, cholesterol pills, vitamins, and a drug for the patient's brain due to the stroke.    On 17 Feb 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot #: 031M20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 17 Feb 2021, ten minutes after receiving the vaccination, the patient began to shake, patient's head and arm shocked and patient was completely out with eyes closed. The reporter stated it looked like the patient wasn't breathing. Seven minutes later, the patient was given an epi shot and oxygen. The patient was transported via ambulance to the emergency room (ER). At that time, a scan was performed - nothing was detected in patient's brain. Patient remained in ER from 0830 to 1500. Patient subsequently left ER very weak and a little confused. It was recommended for patient not to receive second vaccination dose.    Treatment information included epi shot and oxygen.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported.    The events began to shake, head and arm shocked, completely out/eyes were closed, and looked like he wasn't breathing were considered resolved on 17 Feb 2021.  The events very weak and little confused were not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Stroke (about 2 months ago)

Within one minute of receiving vaccine, the patient became pale, stated that he felt dizzy and fainted.  Patient regained consciousness within one minute.  Upon regaining consciousness, patient reported feeling lightheaded and dizzy but was oriented to person, place and time.  Skin was warm and dry but pale in color.  After regaining consciousness, patient also stated that he has a history of fainting 5-6 years ago after receiving an influenza vaccination. (During screening questions, patient denied having any reactions to vaccines in the past) Patient independently moved from a chair to a laying down position on a cot and expressed an improvement in how he was feeling.  Vital signs taken after event as recorded below.  When asked patient stated that he does recall times when he thinks he may have been hypoglycemic in the past. Patient also states that he has been very nervous about receiving injections throughout his life.  EMS called and assessed patient at the vaccination clinic site.  Patient drank a 10 oz bottle of orange juice prior to EMS arriving and when EMS staff obtained his blood sugar the result was 97.  EMS stated that patient was stable and all vital signs were stable.  Patients skin color improved to pink.  Patients wife was called by patient and she provided transportation home for patient.  Prior to leaving the vaccination clinic, patient was walking around for several minutes and denied any feelings of being lightheaded or dizzy.  VITALS SIGNS: 5:06pm: Heart rate: 50, Oxygen Saturation: 99% on room air 5:15 pm: Blood pressure: 100/78 ; Heart rate: 50; oxygen saturation 99% on room air. 5:20pm: Blood pressure 98/76 Heart rate:52; oxygen saturation 96% on room air. 5:34 pm: Blood pressure 92/68 Heart rate: 53 oxygen saturation 97% on room air. Vital signs taken by EMS staff were not recorded by public health nursing staff.
OTHER_MEDS: Citalopran (Celexa) 20 mg by mouth once a day.
CUR_ILL: Patient denies having any illness at the time of the vaccination.
HISTORY: Patient denies having any history of underlying health conditions. He does state that he believes he has experienced hypoglycemia in the past.  He reports that he recalls feeling shaky when he hasn't eaten for a prolonged period of time.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient reports that he fainted after receiving an influenza vaccine approximately 5-6 years ago.
ALLERGIES: No allergies to medications, food or other products

A 76-year-old female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Lot number EL1283), intramuscularly, on 23Jan2021 at 11:30 (at the age of 76-years-old) as a single dose in the left arm for COVID 19 vaccination. Historical vaccinations included pneumonia vaccine (UNKNOWN MANUFACTURER but reported as "Pneumonia 13") on an unspecified date "four years ago" after which she developed a headache which she attributes to an allergy to unknown preservatives. She never received the second "Pneumonia 13" because of the reaction with the first one. She also reported that she has had this same reaction of headache attributed to allergy to unknown preservatives when eating fast foods and foods with sauces. Concomitant medications were not reported. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within four weeks prior to the vaccination. The vaccine was administered at a County Convention Center.  On 23Jan2021 at 11:45, fifteen minutes after she received the vaccination, the patient developed a headache which she has had ever since she got in on Saturday. She also stated that it feels like "a migraine on steroids."  She did tell the person at the clinic where she received it. She stated that she is "hypoallergenic" and she had to sit for thirty minutes after receiving it. She was already anxious and about fifteen minutes in, she developed the headache and nothing has helped so far. She added that she has not had a headache in a long time and that is why she feels it is the shot. She reported that what she took for treatment did not work. These treatments included: Acetaminophen Extra Strength 500mg NDC 21130-111-90. Lot 9ME2806A, expiration 20Jul2021. Count size is 500 caplets, Motrin Ibuprofen tablets 200mg. Lot 6ME1058A, Expiration Sep2018. Count size 100 caplets which when taken was an expired product, SalonPas Roll On Lot 192498, Expiration Jan2022. Count size is 1 container with 3 fluid ounces or 88ml and Neck Wrap and Wrist Heat Wraps which is reported as "a generic equivalent of Thermacare" with Lot number 91211OC16, Expiration 10Dec2022. She did not take the heavy duty Motrin because it was out of date. She commented that all of these things had helped in the past. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I saw bright red dots &dot clusters on both legs; Petechiae; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer reported for herself.  A 58-years-old female patient (not pregnant at the time of vaccination) received her first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), lot number: EL9262, via an unspecified route of administration on 02Feb2021 13:30 in left arm at single dose for covid-19 immunisation.  Medical history included known allergies: Amoxicillin (all penicillin family), she had AT III deficiency (a hereditary blood clotting disorder) that she had been taking warfarin for 23 years never any issues or clots since.  she had never had a reaction to any vaccines before. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19.  Concomitant medication included warfarin for AT III deficiency and 1 multi vitamin.  The patient previously took amoxicillin and experienced allergies.  On 02Feb2021 the patient got the vaccine at 1:30pm. At 5:30 pm, she saw bright red dots and dot clusters on both legs (not sure when it started, reported as 02Feb2021 05:00 PM) all dots were under the surface of her skin. They didn't itch nor hurt and were not detectable by touch. She took a few pictures. Next day they were still there and hadn't increased or decreased. The next day Thursday, she went to her PCP Dr (Name) got blood work and results came back normal. He thought it to be petechiae but not sure why. Each day the red dot/clusters turned more purple and within 5-7 days had faded away.  Dr. (Name). said if with the second vaccine dose, she got worse dot/clusters that worry her, she was to come back.  On 12Feb2021 she had an appt with her hematologist Dr (Name), after discussing and looking at the pictures (knowing that she had never had this before) she said it was not related to her medical condition-AT3 deficiency, it didn't look like petechiae. She said it was a reaction to the vaccine, to report it and get advice from you folks before got the second dose. There was no treatment received. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The outcome of the events was resolved in Feb2021. The events were reported as non-serious by the reporter.

Delivery at 36,9 weeks of gestation; Vaccine exposure during preganancy; This observational study case, initially received on 30-Oct-2019 from other health professional and concerned a 22-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 160 lbs, height: 63 inches and body mass index (BMI): 28.3, enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's current condition included sickle cell trait, high body mass index and nausea. The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (minerals nos; vitamins nos) for pregnancy and vitamin B6, ondansetron and Unisom (doxylamine succinate) for nausea.   The subject's obstetrical history included two previous pregnancies with one preterm live birth and one spontaneous abortion. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 08-Jul-2019. The subject's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 13-Apr-2020 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 21-Apr-2020. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The pregnancy was complicated by subject's increased BMI and sickle cell trait gene.  On 04-Oct-2019, at approximately 12 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP),  the subject was administered Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL)(influenza vaccine, dose reported as 0.5 mg; route of administration: intramuscular; anatomical location: right deltoid) (explicitly coded as 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100112488.  On the same day, first sequential, nuchal translucency screening test and prenatal panel revealed no MCM. Also, on this day the subject underwent hemoglobinopathy test, which showed maternal sickle cell trait.  At gestational age of 36.9 weeks (as reported), the subject delivered via caesarean method, live birth male neonate. The characteristics of the neonate included birth weight of 2381 grams, head circumference and length were not reported. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores at one, five and ten minutes were not reported. No MCM was identified at birth. No pregnancy complications were noted.   The outcome of 'premature delivery' was not reported.  The event of 'premature delivery' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  This case is linked with 202101464 (the corresponding baby case). The patient's relevant medical history and patient's concomitant medications were not reported.  On 11-Oct-2018, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria (TIV) (influenza vaccine, dose, route of administration, indication and anatomical location: not reported). The batch number reported was YT38207B, expiry date: 30-Jun-2019.   On the same day, that night after receiving Afluria (TIV), the patient felt bad.  On 12-Oct-2018, the patient recovered from event of feeling bad.   On an unspecified day in Oct-2018, reported as the following week, the patient woke up with terrible headache. He went to Urgent Care and was sent to the emergency room. The patient was diagnosed with migraine.    On an unspecified day in Oct-2018, the patient started having infections, inflammatory reactions, abnormal kidney function, Hashimoto Disease, cervical (C)7 radiculopathy, nerve damage, triceps damage, multiple T2 hypersensitivity related to MRI, the benign of nodule in left eye and on thyroid, fibromyalgia, chronic fatigue syndrome, short term memory issues and increased CSF protein.  On 26-Oct-2018, the patient was hospitalised, but no further details were provided.   On 27-Oct-2018, the patient was discharged from hospital.   On an unspecified day in Jan-2020, reported as last January, the patient was diagnosed with post ischemic gliosis on the brain. The patient saw multiple physicians.   On an unspecified date, reported as now, the patient had reactivated virus in central nervous system.   On an unspecified date, the vaccine ruined the patient's nursing career and he was applying for disability and looking into compensation fund.  At the time of initial reporting on 19-Feb-2021, the patient did not recover from the events.  The reporter assessed all events as related. He stated that Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) reported 18 reactions from this lot number and he would like to know if we have performed any quality check (QC). He stated we have immunity from prosecution, and he was sure we do not perform the QC. The vaccine had ruined his nursing career and he was applying for disability and looking into Program for funds. The patient read online that there were bad adverse reactions to squalene.  The events of migraine, 'infection', 'inflammatory reaction', 'cervical radiculopathy', nerve damage, 'muscle damage', 'benign thyroid nodule', 'nodule' and 'fibromyalgia' were assessed as serious due to the criterion of hospitalization. The event of 'impaired work ability' was assessed as serious due to criterion of disability.  Company Comment: A 49-year-old male patient developed renal impairment, autoimmune thyroiditis, migraine, infection, inflammation, cervical radiculopathy, nerve injury, muscle injury, benign neoplasm of thyroid gland and nodule (both reported as benign nodule in left eye and on thyroid), fibromyalgia, impaired work ability, viral infection (reported as reactivated virus in central nervous system), gliosis (reported as post ischemic gliosis) and feeling abnormal after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria (TIV). Patient became non-verbal and stat imaging revealed an acute hemorrhage in the left occipatal lobe likely representing a SAH.  Patient then transferred to another hospital that could provide neurosurgical intervention.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: itching and aching in muscle of left arm followed by redness spreading towards elbow

On February 14, I had used the handlebar rotation exercise of a stationery bike for 5 minutes.  The next day I noticed a large swelling about the size of half a pear on the muscle where my Moderna injection was done.  It was as hard as a nut, red, and warm and itchy with a red rash around it.  I saw an urgent care medical person and was told it was probably a reaction to the exercise and that sometimes that happens after an injection.  I was told to use cold compresses, hydrocortison cream, and rest it.  I did this, for 5 days, but  though the swelling subsided, the rash continued to move around and down my arm.  I went back to urgent care on February 19 and was told that it looked better.  I was offered prednazone for it, but declined since I was still on Budesonide .  I was told it would probably clear up over the weekend.  On February 22  it hadn't cleared up so I saw  a PC.  She  noted the rash  had spread, but swelling had gone down.  She checked my lymph node under my left arm and noticed it was swollen.  She said it was most likely due to a mild infection in the arm where I had  received the vaccination.  She  prescribed  a Zpack and after 2 days, all symptoms were gone and I felt so much better.  This event happened 10 days after my vaccination.
OTHER_MEDS: 1 Centrum Silver, two 600 mg calcium & vitamin D3, one 81 mg aspirin, one 5mg amlodipine besylate, on 20 mg omeprazole, 3 mg budesonide
CUR_ILL: recovering from infectious colitis diagnosed on 11/2/20

Diagnosed with May-thurner syndrome; Deep vein thrombosis; Both of her feet were only slightly swollen; Dull minor headache; Off-label use; Inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered; Localized discomfort where injection of second dose of Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine was given; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient).   A 65-year-old female patient (weight: 77.56 kg, height: 157 cm) received the second dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-Biontech Covid-19 Vaccine) at single dose, in the upper left arm, on 23Jan2021, for COVID-19 immunisation. Relevant medical history included thyroid condition from an unspecified date (over 25-30 years before this report) and ongoing, controlled with levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID); and breast cancer from an unspecified date, in 2019 (treatment and surgery on an unspecified date, in 2019. Presumed resolved with radiation treatment, but no treatment within a year prior to getting Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine). The patient previously, on 05Jan2021 (18 days before the second dose), received the first dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-Biontech Covid-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 immunisation. After the first dose, the patient experienced localized discomfort at the injection site and swelling of feet. Concomitant medication included levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID) from an unspecified date and ongoing, 0.88 mg, daily, for thyroid condition. On 23Jan2021, the patient experienced injection site discomfort described as "localized discomfort where injection of second dose of Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine was given". On 24Jan2021, she had dull minor headache. On an unspecified date, the patient was hospitalized after the second dose and was diagnosed with May-thurner syndrome. She clarified that May-Thurner syndrome was where the iliac artery collapses and crushed the iliac vein in the upper abdomen; from that point down it started creating a blood clot. She developed a deep vein thrombosis (DVT) from her left ankle up to her right rib cage area; it was a monster. On 10Feb2021, the patient experienced deep vein thrombosis and thrombectomy was performed on the same day (outpatient thrombectomy surgery, performed 10Feb2021. It was a great surgery, very corrective. She never did have any pain or discomfort which confused everyone. She felt fine this whole time, no issues). On an unspecified date, both of her feet were only slightly swollen. Relevant laboratory test, performed on an unspecified date, in 2021, included computerised tomogram (CT scan with contrast of her abdomen and chest) that showed deep vein thrombosis: left ankle-right ribcage area. The adverse events May-Thurner syndrome and deep vein thrombosis were assessed as serious, hospitalization required from 02Feb2021 to 10Feb2021. The patient recovered from deep vein thrombosis on 10Feb2021, recovered from headache on 26Jan2021, recovered from swelling of feet and vaccination site discomfort on an unspecified date, while clinical outcome of the other events was unknown. Her vascular surgeon said he did not believe these events were vaccine related but cannot rule it out; her Primary Care Physician absolutely believed the events were vaccine related.   The information on the lot number has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first injection of the COVID-19 vaccine on 12/28/2020 and the second dose on 01/12/2021. Starting  Friday February 5, I developed severe itching on my back that occurred during sleep only. The itching continued for the next several nights. I had to remove my bra in order to obtain any sleep. After removing the bra, the itching eventually stopped. I tried several bras, but all caused itching at bedtime only. Now, itching is occurring on other parts of my body. Hives and itching have developed on my back, chest, inner thighs and both hands. The itching is relieved by applying lotion. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Low birth weight of 2438 g; This is an observational study case, initially received on 19-Feb-2021 from other health professional and concerned a male neonate, whose mother was 18-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight 121 lbs, height 64.5 inches and body mass index (BMI) 20.4, enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.   The maternal concurrent conditions included anaemia and gestational thrombocytopenia. The mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (minerals not specified (nos), vitamins nos) used for pregnancy, Injectafer (ferric carboxymaltose), ferrous sulfate and Ferralet (ferrous gluconate), all used for anemia.  The maternal obstetrical history noted that the neonate's mother had no previous pregnancies. The mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The neonate's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 30-Jul-2019, the estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 05-May-2020, while the corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 11-May-2020. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 24-Sep-2019, the ultrasound scan revealed no MCM.  On 29-Oct-2019, non-invasive prenatal test and nuchal translucency revealed no MCMs.  On 26-Nov-2019, maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein screening (MSAFP), serum markers revealed no MCMs.  On 07-Jan-2020, at approximately 23 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP), the neonate's mother was administered Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine; dose, anatomical location and route of administration: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100112488.  On the same day, 20-week anatomy ultrasound scan revealed no MCM.  At gestational age of 37 weeks (as reported), the mother delivered vaginally a live birth, male neonate. The neonate birth weight was 2438 grams, head circumference and length were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores at one, five and 10 minutes were not provided. No MCM was identified at birth.  The outcome of the event was not reported.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The event of 'low birth weight baby' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked with the case 202002354, the corresponding mother case.  Company comment: A male neonate patient experienced low birth weight, approximately 14 weeks after maternal receipt of Afluria QIV. Chronology is plausible. As reported, the maternal obstetrical history noted that the neonate's mother had no previous pregnancies. The mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The neonate's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The ultrasound scan revealed no MCM. With currently available information, causality for the event low birth weight is unassessable. The event foetal exposure during pregnancy was assessed as not related considering the intended use of the vaccine.      .; Sender's Comments: A male neonate patient experienced low birth weight, approximately 14 weeks after maternal receipt of Afluria QIV. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received COVID vaccine 1 on 1/13 and COVID vaccine #2 2/1.  49 y/o previously healthy female who had a COVID 19 exposure ~ 1/3. The person she was exposed to tested positive 1/6 (daughter had a fever and cough). On 1/11 the patient received the 1st dose of the Pfizer vaccine. 12-24 hours after the Pfizer vaccine she developed fevers, malaise, myalgias that lasted 2-3 days (Called off work). She then returned to a normal state of health. On 2/1 she received the second dose of the vaccine. On 2/6 she developed right pleuritic chest pain so went to an urgent care. COVID 19 PCR was positive and CXR unremarkable. She was told to take naproxen and her pleuritic chest pain slowly improved. On 2/8 she started to have general malaise followed by nausea. On 2/11 she developed increased nausea and vomiting followed by diarrhea-eventually that day she had a near syncopal episode prompting her presentation to the hospital. Seen at an outside hospital between 2/11-2/12. CT abd/pelvis showed patchy ground glass opacities at the base of the lungs and she was noted to have diffuse mural thickening. There was concern for possible cholecystitis so a perc cholecystostomy tube was placed. Ultimately she developed significant hypoxic respiratory failure and had to be intubated.She was transferred to another hospital on 2/12. Initially she was started on treatment with dexamethasone but continued to clinically get worse. Also on empiric antibiotics.
LAB_DATA: CT chest revealed diffuse patchy and consolidative groudglass opacities. TTE showed an EF of 30%.  Significant labs included AKI (cr 3.5), AST 86, ALT 60, ferritin 3462, LDH 331, troponin 0.567, wbc 25, platelets dropped 50 to 11, procalcitonin 38, CK 940.  Repeat covid PCR from nares and sputum was negative on 2/16.   Suspicion for MIS-A: started as the inflammatory markers increased and we were unable to determine another source for infection: CRP 300, ferritin increased to 8100, LDH increased 1400, procalcitonin remained elevated at 43, BNP 160K, trop increased to 1.1, marked thrombocytopenia continued (TTP and ITP ruled out) and elevated LFTs. IL 1 1.1 and IL 6 67. Also had worsening respiratory status and hemodynamics.  Treatment course: 2/17 the suspicion became higher as the inflammatory markers peaked and we discussed the case with our pediatric MIS-C colleagues. Received a dose of IVIG (1.2grams) and started methylpred 1 gram x 3 days. On 2/18 we started anakinra. After the 3 days of high dose methypred we changed to 1 mg/kg BID. She has also received 2 more doses of IVIG.
OTHER_MEDS: COVID vaccine #1 on 1/13/21 and COVID vaccine #2 2/1/21 Naproxen started 2/6/21-prn medication for chest pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 36 Hours following the vaccine shot, I noticed a number of dark spots under my arms and on my back. A trip to the Dermatologist on Monday 2/15/2021 determined that the vaccine had caused most if not all of the Seborrheic Keratoses (SK's) skin growths on my body to change color to a blue color. Four or the SK's were removed and sent to the lab for biopsy. The result came back as irritated SK's but no mention was made of the discoloration. After one week Friday (2/19), the blue color began to fade and by Sunday (2/20) the smaller of the SK's had returned to their original color while the larger still retain some of the blue color. During this time I felt fine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the vaccine, I just had a mild headache and mild leg aches, off and on, and took Advil twice with complete relief. Then I was fine until 7th day when I awoke a 7am. I felt mentally "weird" and couldn't concentrate. Not dizzy. I ate my normal breakfast of lox, cream cheese and bread with coffee with cream and Stevia. I sat at the computer and could not concentrate or even read well, and felt confused at times. Then I got hot and sweaty, my mouth got very dry, I had pains and needles over my entire body, and the tip of my tongue got numb. I laid down in my bed and felt worse. My blood pressure was 160-170/105-110, and normally it is 120-135-70-84.  I thought maybe I was having a neurological event, so I had my wife take me to the ER. I was there about 6 hours, but after about 3-4 hours, let better. The symptoms would come and go, lasting 3-5 minutes, and slowly improved. After the 2nd treponin was negative, they let me go home. I felt tired and mentally off a little. I rested. The next am, I was back to normal and have stayed OK since.
LAB_DATA: In ER, all was normal. My blood pressure was 170/105 to start and in a hour or so came down to 130/80. I was monitored and it was normal, except fast pulse at start, about 100, which dropped to 70s in a hour or so. CBC, electrolytes, basic chemistries, treponin x 2, EKG all normal. Basic exam including neuro exam by ER Dr. were normal. She consulted with my cousin who is my cardiologist by phone. They both agreed that my symptoms didn't match any common problems and agreed that it was likely an unusual delayed vaccine reaction. I agree as I do have general allergies, even though I have never had a vaccine reaction in my life.
OTHER_MEDS: lipitor 40, ASA 81, losartan 50, hctz 12.5, lots of vitamins. No change in these for a long time
ALLERGIES: tobramycin, and environmental allergies to cats, trees, grasses, and ?some foods

Patient reported symptoms of: tachycardia, shakiness, vision changes, tongue numbness and shortness of breath following the first dose of the COVID19 Pfizer-BioNTech Vaccine on 2/5/2021. Patient said that historically has experienced tachycardia and shakiness after getting a flu shot or booster a few years ago. Symptoms reported by patient were enough to suspect potential anaphylaxis, and patient consented pharmacist to administer epinephrine. Patient was then advised by the pharmacist to follow-up with her primary care doctor as soon as possible to report the incident and to discuss the risk versus benefit of the vaccine, whether recieving the second dose would be appropriate for her. Patient returned to assisted living facility for her second dose of the COVID19 Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine on 2/26/2021. Patient said that she discussed the incident with her doctor, was told it would be appropriate to get the second dose despite her reaction and was advised to take "cautious measures". Pharmacist reviewed the patient information and screening questions, discussed the potential side effects and reiterated her risk of experiencing the same reaction with the second dose. Patient stated that she decided on getting the second dose because "her boyfriend is high risk and I'm doing this for him". Patient stated that she decided on getting the second dose because "her boyfriend is high risk and I'm doing this for him". Pharmacist asked patient if she had any questions/concerns or additional information to add prior to getting her vaccine, and patient denied having any at that time. After administering her second dose, pharmacist instructed patient to stay in the observation area for at least 30 minutes and to ask the staff for water given her experience with the first dose.  Patient asked pharmacist how common it was for someone to get a reaction from the vaccine, and then mentioned that her family memeber had to drive her to the emergency room after her first dose becuase her throat was "burning", and was told that her throat was "a little swollen" and recieved a second dose of epinephrine at the emergency room. Patient included this information after the fact her second dose was already administered.  Approximately 5 minutes after receving her vaccine, the patient reported similar symptoms that she experienced on 2/5/2021: tachycardia, vision changes, shortness of breath and chest tightness. After monitoring patient with no resolvement of her symptoms, patient was then given a dose of epinephrine by the pharmacist, and the paramedics were called in to assess patient and take her to the emergency room.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient reports using a rescue inhaler PRN. No other prescriptions, OTC or herbal supplement were reported by patient.
CUR_ILL: Patient denied having any illnesses one month prior from 2/26/2021 besides having a reaction to the first dose of the COVID vaccine.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient was 20 years old, reported similar reaction to first dose of COVID19 Pfizer-BioNTech Vaccine on 2/5/2021.
ALLERGIES: Patient reported no known allergies to any medications. Patient said her allergies to food included: eggs, coconut and milk.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt given 0.5cc COVID #2 injection (Moderna), was waiting in patient area for 30 minutes due to h/o other reactions previously. 20 minutes after injection, pt remarked that she felt hot.  Brought back to resp clinic, wasn't having any SOB or CP, didn't appear very flushed.  Was shaking. Pulse ox applied, O2 stayed between 98 & 99% RA.  HR was initially in high 80's (pt on 50mg metoprolol QD), climbed up to 109. BP (lg cuff, rt arm) was 144/91.  Pt became nauseated, vomited phlegm.  Did not feel presyncope.  Ice applied to back of neck. No redness at injection site.  Heart exam: no murmurs or irregular heartbeat; lungs CTA throughout, no stridor or wheezing. Pt remarked that the heart racing, shakiness & heat felt like previous times when she was given racemic epi for reactions.  Was monitored for 30 minutes, HR stabilized in low 80's, sensation of heat dissipated.  Was allowed to leave 50 minutes after vaccination given, and advised to call for EMT if symptoms came back.  She expressed understanding, and was told to NOT drive herself home (family member was with her).
OTHER_MEDS: metoprolol 50mg QD, Xanax 0.5mg TID PRN, Elavil 50mg @ HS, Lyrica 150mg QHS

February 21, 2021 around 4 pm, a woman on the passenger  seat of a car, driven by her husband began feeling ? dizzy?. I was approached by our CIO to see her immediately. Another Nurse  came to the rescue and we both assessed the patient. She was awake, alert, oriented but anxious and stating she's dizzy. The back of the seat was lowered down for her comfort and blood pressure was taken. It was 172 /100 mmhg. PR = 72 , Temp = 97.5. RR = 18. Two other RNs came to help. The patient was conversant, her husband was upbeat and being funny. Pt started to play with her dog from the backseat reaching for it. The patient was talking but I decided to tell patient to relax since vital signs will be taken again. BP repeated after 6 minutes and its now 155/100, PR= 75, RR=19, TEMP= 97.3, 02 Sat @89 % . Pt?s hands were cold now. O2 Sat was also hard to get a good reading on all of her fingers. Called Dr. Cat Forest and she came to the scene comforting patient while vitsal signs were repeated again after 5 minutes  after they were taken Now getting BP=  55/110 mmhg, PR: 80, Temp 97.2 and O2 Sat still at 89% Pt was adviced to go the ER after the Patient?s O2 Sat stayed at 89% and also after finding out that patient haven?t had any physical for two years and that patient doesnt check her blood pressure. Pt and her husband were counselled on the importance of getting regular check up especially at her age of 69 years old. Husband drove patient to the ER per order. Called patient on Monday, 2/23 and Tuesday, 2/24 with no answer. emailed patient and patient answered back and she said that she went to the ER with her husband that day and was discharged and feeling better and wanting to thank the staff for the way she was taken cared of and hoping they will be there for her second dose when she comes back.
LAB_DATA: Patient did not share this info when asked .

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received first covid vaccine 1/17/21 to the right deltoid (Pfizer, lot #EL3248). On 1/27/21 seen by an APNP for right arm pain and decreased mobility. Presented to EHS on 1/29/21 with pain and concern that vaccine was give posterior to the deltoid. Pt did not take pictures or get seen around the time of her vaccine. So, 12 days later, unable to verify exact placement of the vaccine back on 1/17/21.  Per the APNP's report on 1/27/21, the pt developed sharp shooting pain into the right trap/scapular area and radiation to lower arm. The pain started within a few seconds after the covid-19 vaccine was given. Feels soreness and tension in the shoulder/scapular area which has not resolved since vaccine. Pt advised continue supportive cares, trial diclofenac gel, use oral NSAIDs cautiously, apply heat. Follow up with EMG (scheduled for 4/14/21). Pt was also given a prescription for cyclobenzaprine.  Per documented telephone encounters, as of 2/26/21 pt continues to have significant pain.  Note: Pt received her second covid-19 vaccine on 2/13/21 in her left deltoid and there has been no mention of issues with pain in the left arm (Pfizer, lot #EN5318)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3-5 minutes after receiving the vaccine, I felt a sense of panic and a tingling on my lips, that then spread to my mouth, throat, and tongue. I asked the nurse if my lips were swollen, and she said no.  A few minutes later my heart rate increased and I felt really lightheaded. After 7-10 minutes I felt my tongue tingling and it had become swollen. I told the nurse that I think my tongue was swollen and she said it looked okay. I had a hard time talking because I wasn't used to be tongue being so large. The nurses stayed and talked to me for the rest of the 30 minute waiting period. I was able to talk and breath while making a conscious effort.  I wasn't sure whether the high heart rate and lightheadedness were associated with my condition, Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome. I kept checking my tongue to see how swollen it was.  After the 30 minutes, the nurses had me stand up to see if I could. Once I could, they said I was all set to go. They did not get an Epi-pen for the swollen tongue or give me instructions on how to treat it. They were insensitive and dismissive of my symptoms. they kept repeating "I think your just nervous." Once I got home, I still had the swollen tongue and tingling, but was able to go up and down stairs and go about my day. It was a little difficult to swallow one of my pills when I got home, but I was able to. I checked my blood pressure around 4:30 p.m. and it was 121/84 and my pulse was 79 bpm sitting. I did not take anything to treat my swollen tongue. The swollen tongue and tingling feeling in my throat continued for another 2.5 hours, until 6:00 p.m. Once the swelling was down, my tongue felt like I burnt it on a hot beverage, almost a numb feeling. I also experienced more common side effects such as body aches, fatigue, and feeling feverish.   After this episode I had extremely high anxiety where it was difficult for me to sleep the following night. I called a 24/7 nurse line and she said to talk to my doctor. I had less than 4 hours sleep the night after I had my vaccine.  I called my doctor's office this morning and I spoke to a nurse who worked as a nurse on the COVID Vaccine hotline.  She relayed the message to the doctor who was covering for my doctor while she's on medical leave. I received a call around 9:30 a.m. saying that the doctor on leave recommend I should talk to my PCP but that she thought I had an allergic reaction to the Pfizer vaccine and that I should not get the second dose. She said they were not sure how I would react with the second dose, and they're afraid that my allergic response might be more severe and life threatening.  I hope this report helps other people who experience these symptoms.

HISTORY: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome, Migraines, Hives.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the usual flu-like symptoms starting around 9 pm the day of the vaccination 24th) - headache, chills, lethargy, loss of appetite, injection site pain. I didn't notice anything else overnight, exception injection site pain increased. The next morning I got up around 6:45 am to feed my pets. I felt woozy walking about 25 m from the bedroom to the pet food location, and also very flushed and hot. I started sweating copiously while I was getting the food out, and then I fainted. I don't know how long I was unconscious but I suspect not more than a minute or two. I didn't seem to injure myself when I fell, other than a bruised elbow and hip I was able to finish feeding the pets, crawl to the bathroom (I had a strong accompanying urge to evacuate my bowels), and then get into bed. I went back to sleep at around 7:15 am and by 10:00 am I felt more normal, still with some chills and headache, general lethargy, and not much appetite. Those symptoms lasted through the evening until I went to bed at 9:00 pm, gradually decreasing. Today I feel mostly fine, although dehydrated. I did not record my temperature during the fever spike, nor receive medical attention.
Rash

Excerpt taken from patient's medical record notes.    Recreational Therapist was in room with patient who was at baseline mentation at that time, and was getting patient a cup of tea.  Rec Therapist observed patient to "all of a sudden slouch down toward left side" and became unresponsive.  Therapist called for help, and Registered Nurse (RN) and Certified Nurse Aide (CNA) came into room.  Patient was initially non-responsive and profusely sweating and hot to touch.  Vitals  were taken (see below).  The patient then slowly became responsive after approximately 4 minutes and was visibly nauseous  and appeared like she was going to vomit, but ultimately did not.  Patient was assisted into bed, APRN was called, order for vital signs to be taken every 4 hours for 72 hours, and Electrocardiogram (EKG) to be performed.   EKG results were abnormal, indicative of infarct; APRN ordered transport to Emergency Department.   Patient returned from Hospital ED at approximately 10:45 PM same day (1/28/21), with transfer paperwork documenting  a  Hospital diagnosis of "Syncope" without any additional lab results or any new medication or treatment orders in the documentation.  Follow up the next day (1/29/21) by RN at the Nursing Facility--RN logged into the Hospital medical Charting system, only to find that there was no record whatsoever of the patient being in the Emergency Department on 1/28/21--no notes, no labs, no summary from a practitioner.  Patient recovered and has resumed close-to-baseline activity and functioning.
LAB_DATA: Vitals during the 4 minute unresponsive episode:  B/P 140/62, Apical Pulse Rate 60, Respirations 16, Temperature 97.8 F, O2Sat 93% on room air. EKG at  Nursing Facility:  QT 382 ms, QTC 415 ms     EKG device printout summary: "Supraventricular Arrhythmia.  Abnormality consistent with anteroseptal infarct"

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt arrived for 2nd dose of vaccine today patient stated that she did have a previous reaction of hives, rash, and itching for 2 weeks status post 1st vaccine dose. 12:20- Pt given 2nd dose of vaccine by this nurse and began monitoring on stretcher. 12:33-Pt stated she was experiencing some dizziness and itching to the left posterior neck 1235-Pt stated she was now experiencing itching to the back and noticed some increased work of breathing and redness to her left side of the neck. Patient stated: " Hard to breath and it feels like I am unable to take a deep breath." 1237-Provider and medics on duty notified and patient assessed and patient's VSS and lungs clear to auscultation. Provider ordered Benadryl 25mg oral liquid to be given to the patient. 1237: Patient given Benadryl 25mg Benadryl by nurse. Patient observation continued and it was found that after calling patient's mother that the patient did have a reaction to the Typhoid Vaccine in the past with a noted PEG Allergy.  Patient denies any other allergies but does take allergy injections and her last dose was 2/8/21.  Provider spoke with patient and patient's mother who came to pick up the patient that the recommendation at this point would be to follow up with either Urgent care of Emergency room due to the known PEG Allergy. Mother arrived and pt was to be transported via private vehicle to Urgent care. Patient strongly encourage to establish with a PCP and after speaking with the Lead provider it was noted that the patient could go home with mother but monitoring should occur at home and the patient should take another dose of Benadryl 25mg four house after the initial dose of Benadryl.  Patient and mother educated of this and communicated understanding. 1337: Provider gave detailed discharge instruction to the patient and when also when to follow up if any swelling, increased itching, hives, or worsening of shortness of breath should occur. Pt should take additional precautionary dose of Benadryl 25mg at 1630. 13:40-Patient denied any further itching and redness had decreased.  Patient discharged home with mother and mother also stated that if needed there is an Epi Pen in the house and readily available if needed.
ALLERGIES: PEG (unknown product, unknown reaction), Typhoid vaccine (unknown reaction)

Pt has a history of multiple drug allergies including anaphylaxis. Prior to COVID 19 vaccination we discussed her reaction to previous Pneumovax 12 years prior. Several minutes following administration of the Pneumovax, she developed scratchy throat and hoarseness. Benadryl was administered with improvement in symptoms. She did not require epinephrine or ER visit. We discussed that she had a higher risk of reaction to the COVID 19 vaccine and advised her to wait 30 minutes post injection. During her wait time she began to develop scratchy throat and hoarseness that progressed over 10 minutes. She was taken to the treatment area where vital signs were obtained and 50 mg of oral Benadryl was given.    Initial VS were SpO2 of 98, P 82, BP 140/100. She was alert and oriented. No edema lips or tongue. Heart RRR Lungs CTAB with no wheezes.    She remained under observation for 30 minutes, vital signs remained stable and BP ranges from 138-140/80-90. She had noticable improvement in her throat and voice and she was discharged in good condition to home under the care of her husband.   They were advised that Benadryl could be repeated in 4-6 hours if needed. Should she develop any facial swelling, shortness of breath, wheezing or lightheadedness they should proceed to the emergency department.    Reviewed the newly updated CDC guidance on reactions. Although her reaction was immediate it was not considered severe. CDC advised against getting the second vaccine. She is advised to discuss further with her allergist, Dr if she would like to discuss the possibility of getting the second dose with premedication or other precaution.    She and her husband understood well and all questions answered.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday morning 2/26/21, we had a 24 yo male patient who had an anaphylactic reaction after his first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine. He was instructed to wait on the chair, but had stood up at some point but was still in the pharmacy waiting area. A team member noticed he had fainted and called for help. The pharmacist on duty and immunizing tech came immediately to help him to a chair. At that point, he was conscious and talking. Then within a few seconds he started convulsing on the chair and lost consciousness. His eyes were open and head tilted back. A team member immediately called 911 and pharmacist administered 0.3mg Epipen to the thigh. We removed his face mask to check his breathing and also to allow him to breathe more easily. We also adjusted his head more forward and he started coughing. After about 15 seconds, he regained consciousness and could answer questions. EMT arrived soon after and took over. Patient does not have allergies or any history of anaphylaxis/ severe reaction from vaccinations. He did express some fear of needles and did not eat breakfast yet.

loss of consciousness;febrile Narrative: Patient received his 2nd vaccine at 10am 2/17. That evening he felt subjectively febrile and then suffered a ground level fall at 0400 on 2/18. He did not lose consciousness or injure his head. EMS was contacted and assisted him into bed. At 0600, wife noted increased work of breathing, which prompted another EMS call, who found him hypoxic with fever of 106. He was transported to a community hospital, where he was found to have temp 102.9 and blood pressure in 70s-80s systolic. He was transferred to hospital at 1300 on 2/18/21, requiring norepinephrine for pressure support after fluid resuscitation. He c/o stiffness and soreness all over but presenting ROS was otherwise negative. Patient was treated with 4L IV fluids and vancomycin and piperacillin/tazobactam at the outside ER. Here at the hospital he was treated with vancomycin, piperacillin/tazobactam and levofloxacin along with IV fluids and norepinephrine. Despite this he had several fevers with Tmax 103.5F the night of 2/18-2/19 and he required norepinephrine plus vasopressin overnight to maintain blood pressure. Piperacillin/Tazobactam was discontinued in favor of meropenem. His last fever was at 6am on 2/19. ID consult was obtained 2/19/21 and vancomycin and levofloxacin were weaned off. Ultimately his blood pressure improved and he was weaned off of all vasopressors the morning of 2/20. Notably, he never developed severe hypoxemia at rest while in the ICU, but did require BiPAP non-invasive ventilation at night instead of his usual CPAP to keep his oxygen levels > 90% while sleeping and additionally had desaturations into the low 80% range with exertion from which he was slow to recover. His oxygen saturation was >90% on 30-40% FiO2 via aerosol mask overnight and 3L (his current baseline) NC during the day. He was transferred out of the ICU on 2/21 based on hemodynamic improvement, stable oxygenation, and improved mentation and symptoms. Unfortunately, on the morning of 2/22/21, patient had an abrupt change in status and was found to be unresponsive with hypercarbic respiratory failure and hypotension. ABG during this event was 7.16/121/65. BiPAP was initiated as patient's code status was DNR/DNI. CXR with no significant change from 2/18/21. CT of head without contrast was negative for acute processes. Based on lack of rapid improvement, the decision was made by wife to transition to comfort care. Patient died at 1446 on 2/22/21. **Of note: patient was admitted for 1 week for covid 19 pneumonia November 2020. During this hospitalization he was found to have chronic R sided PE, no acute PE.
LAB_DATA: Rapid covid test was negative. Admission labs 2/18/21: CBC with WBC of 10.1, H/H 9.6/31.5, plts 167. Lactate WNL. UA with 3+ blood/>100 urine RBC/HPF, 4 WBC/HPF, no culture.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: [COVID-19 mRNA vaccine (Pfizer-BioNtech] treatment under Emergency Use Authorization (EUA)
HISTORY: 61 yo F with history of bilateral lung transplant 6/23/17 presented to ED on 2/4/21 with chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath, nausea and diarrhea for past week since receiving since receiving COVID-19 vaccine (Pfizer) on 1/28/21. Upon arrival to triage she was obviously dyspneic with significantly low oxygen saturations. O2 sats on arrival were 65%, improved to mid 90's with O2 6 liters per NC. Admitting diagnosis: hypoxic respiratory failure post COVID vaccine. Lab work shows an elevation of the BUN and creatinine at 31 and 1.71 which is slightly higher than her usual baseline levels. BNP is elevated at 2 448 with a mildly elevated troponin. Procalcitonin is also elevated. Patient's white blood cell count is 11/07. Full viral panel including COVID-19 is not detected. All blood cultures and respiratory cultures were negative. Patient chest x-ray shows numerous bilateral patchy opacities which is significantly different from her previous chest x-ray here. Empiric rejection treatment initiated including high dose methylprednisolone, plasmapheresis, IVIG, Thymoglobulin. She continued to decline and ultimately required intubation, proning and paralyzing on 2/8/2021 and the VV ECMO cannulation on 2/13/2021. EGD done 2/14/2021 as unable to pass the TEE probe during cannulation prior day (unable to complete due to abnormal anatomy). Acute pupil exam change in the early am hours of 2/15/2021 prompted urgent head CT which revealed catastrophic brain bleed. Brainstem reflexes were lost soon after. Despite placing an EVD emergently at bedside, brain stem reflexes were not recovered. GOL engaged and patient not an organ donation candidate. Therefore discussion with sister at bedside resulted in decision for cessation of life support. Patient expired shortly after support withdrawn and pronounced dead on 2/15/2021 at 11:11 AM.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA The patient was in his usual state of health until he received his second dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on Tuesday 2/23. He had previously had no side effects from the first dose other than soreness at the injection site. After the 2nd dose, he noticed arm soreness at the injection site more quickly than before. 10-12 hours later, he noticed headache and subjective fever, which was relieved by Tylenol. On Wednesday he woke up with subjective fever and chills, and felt sternal chest pain during deep breathing and attempted cough, but did not notice any effect from positional changes. Other than attempting to cough to elicit pain, he did not experience any other symptoms such as runny nose, coughing, sneezing, congestion,  shortness of breath, palpitations, abdominal pain, diarrhea, or dysuria. The following day, he noticed that the chest pain was more severe and persistent throughout the day.  The pain location would vary from the sternal area to the left side of his chest. The intensity of pain would vary between a 2-3/10 to 7-8/10. When the pain peaked, it would be accompanied by feelings of fever, chills, and brief headache, and he felt that the pain would "spread" across his chest. The pain would persist for a variable amount of time but then eventually disappear before returning. The pain was not affected by deep breath, position, or analgesics (he took an ibuprofen at around 2 AM when he couldn't sleep). After he fell asleep he was not woken up by pain. On Friday, he pain continued to be intermittent, and peaked during a work meeting. At that point he told his boss and an MD co-worker, who recommended that he presented to the ED. The EKG that was obtained in triage showed sinus tachycardia widespread ST elevations, PR depressions, with reciprocal changes in aVR. At this time he was continuing to experience chest pain. After getting a room in the ED, he no longer felt pain. He received a 2nd EKG showing improvement in ST elevations in some, but no all leads. He received ibuprofen and he continued to feel no symptoms. He was found to have a troponin elevation of 8.84 that peaked to 11.2. Transthoracic echo showed no motional wall abnormalities, normal EF, no pericardial effusion. He was admitted to the CICU out of concern and workup for myopericarditis.
LAB_DATA: 2/26: EKG, Transthoracic Echo, d-dimer, lactate, SARS-COV2, Viral panel

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No initial symptoms other than sore arm at injection site which lasted for about 23 hours. On January 28 in the middle of the night woke up with pain in left hand. Could not move left hand. Was sleeping on back - not on arm or hand.  No restricted blood-flow.  Massaged hand and it became responsive.  This was followed by burning and tingling sensation in hand.  Hand was cold to touch first day. Burning and tingling and muscle tension increased for first couple days.  Would be intermittent and location varied. Hands and feet most common. Left back scapular area and left pectoral muscle common.  Muscle tightness would cause joint pain without signs of any redness. No temperature. No discoloration. Not as bad in middle of the day. After a few days. When second shot was administered on February 9 at 12:10 AM went home and all sensations stopped for about 12 hours. Took Tylenol with some benefit to diminish but not end symptoms. In past few days have read about taking antihistamines which has often helped.  Symptoms are not as intense as they started out to be, but they continue to linger.  Muscle tightness has largely given way to fluttering sensation or paresthesia and burning is mostly in bottom of left foot only. Any muscle tightness can be rubbed out (massage) for the most part. Occasional joint tightness continues in fingers - crack knuckles and it improves.
LAB_DATA: I am working with a neurologist for balance issues. Three years ago, a neurologist blew off my symptoms after a 3-minute exam. This one has discovered BPPV in left ear - inner ear pressure - loss of balance function in left ear and cervicogenic dizziness.  She prescribed Effexor on January 26, 2021 to mediate peripheral sensations. I took one night and discontinued as agreed upon because I was scheduled for PT and chiropractic treatment. I questioned why we were medicating ahead of those interventions. She agreed. Two days after taking one pill - the symptoms shared - also fit a pattern of withdrawal - and I am sensitive to medications. I have informed neurologist of my symptoms three times not as a complaint but more of an FYI in patient portal and she has made no acknowledgment of the situation.  I let my primary know about the symptoms middle of last week and the response was thanks for letting them know I received the shot and that I might want to consider filing this report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient states approximately 5 minutes after her vaccination, she started to feel like her vision was slightly blurry, then experienced tunnel vision. Pt states felt almost like an "out of body" experience, but she did feel pressure to the left side of her head as she fell off of her chair and her head hit the floor. This fall was witnessed by another patient, who flagged the medical staff for help. A medical assistant notified me of the incident and I went to examine the patient, who was sitting on the floor, alert and conscious. I asked the staff to get the patient an ice pack, which was placed to patient's forehead and back of neck, and glass of water. Patient is able to swallow.   A&O x 3, HR 81 and O2 sat 98% on room air. EOMI, PERRLA. Auscultation of heart & lungs was normal. No bony step-offs palpated. No tenderness upon palpation to patient's head, face and neck/c-spine. No visible contusions, abrasions noted. Normal ROM of all extremities and normal sensation. Observed patient over the course of 15 minutes and patient states she is feeling much better.

Patient states 30 seconds after the injection, she began to feel nauseated. She stated the following symptoms came on "Like a wave": Dizziness, light headedness, ears ringing, sound pulsing, and her vision began to go black. She described the field of vision closing like that of a loony toons show ending (coming from the outside in).   Patient was found to have her eyes closed, hyperventilating at a rate of 28 breaths per minute. Ice pack placed on her neck. She was coached to slow her breathing, instructed to hold her breath for 10 seconds, then to release it slowly. She did this for 3 minutes. She related her body felt tingly all over. Encouraged patient to continue the slow breathing. As patient began to feel better, she related that she has a known needle phobia. She expressed that she becomes anxious even when she is not the one receiving a shot, and this fear stems from a traumatic experience of her son having a seizure after a shot. She works at a school and when they do first aid training and cover the diabetes section, the pictures of needles make her anxious. Patient provided with therapeutic communication, encouraged to discuss fears with her counselor. Patient remained seated in clinic until she felt well enough for her husband to drive her home.
HISTORY: Narcolepsy, fibromyalgia, IBS, Depression, Anxiety, Asthma, Sleep Apnea.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Modern COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I received my COVID vaccine at 7:00pm on 2/22/2021.  At 1:00 am 2/23/2021 I woke up to use the restroom.  I fainted and cut my forehead in the fall.  I was shaking uncontrollably following this.  My husband bandaged my forehead and checked me for a concussion.  Sometime after 2am I realized I was in atrial fibrillation.  I have a Kardia app that confirmed this.  I tried at home methods to go back in rhythm.  At 8am I called my cardiologist.  He advised me to go to the emergency room.  At this time the Kardia app indicated I was no longer in Afib but still had a fast heartbeat.  At the emergency room I had a normal EKG, CAT scan, blood work and chest X-ray and went home about 11am.

On 2/23/21, about 12 days after the vaccine was received, I felt chest pains in the late afternoon.  At midnight, I woke up with uncontrollable chills and shakes, with a low-grade fever that hovered in the 99.5 -100  range.    I attempted to get up and struggled to breathe,; it was as if my abdominal and lower back muscles were seizing.  I had to crawl to a kneeling position to urinate.  I took several Tylenol then went back to lie down; after a few hours, the fever subsided, and I was able to briefly fall back asleep.  At 4:00 a.m. the fever and major chills subsided, with no fevers reported since then, and only occasional chills.  However, the muscle fatigue, pain and stiffness have become frighteningly debilitating.  On Wednesday - Friday, the three days after I first experienced symptoms, each day it took me between 1.5 - 2 hours  to get out of bed and finally get to a standing position.    During the day on each day following my first symptoms, I have been able to gradually walk around, go up and down stairs, use the bathroom, and perform basic tasks.    However, when the evening comes, it is a different story.  12 midnight - 10 a.m. are the worst hours, as any extended period lying down results in my muscles seizing, freezing and stiffening up.  After falling asleep for an hour, it takes 10-20 minutes to mobilize enough (using a crutch and assistance) to get to the bathroom.  After falling asleep for 2-3 hours, it takes 30-40 minutes to do the same.  And, if I fall asleep for 3+ hours (which is about as long as I've been able to sleep since the adverse reactions began), it will take 1.5 - 2 hours to get completely mobile.  This is when I finally wake for the day, and it takes about 10 minutes to raise my head and turn my torso, then another 10-15 minutes to get my legs off the bed and assume a crouching position, then 30-60 minutes to stand on my own.
LAB_DATA: Blood work taken on 2/26/2021  CT scan on 2/26/2021  Neurologist appointment scheduled for 3/1

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Dramatic drop in %SpO2: from a range of 94 - 97, to 88 - 89, with occasional drops to 87. I checked it because I found, even on waking, that I needed to make an effort to breathe more deeply - which did make enough of a difference. In a setting where it would have been available, I am sure I would have received O2. I also had a fever of up to 101.3, and felt "rotten", but not dire. In 2017, I had some sort of incident - I was traveling at the time, and it was never "determined"  - that may have been a "scatter" pulmonary embolism - where the clot breaks apart before distributing into the lung. Initially, I did have quite low %SpO2 readings, but over the years that has improved. But these readings were even lower than I had ever seen. I have two oximeters, to, um, verify each other, so I am reasonably confident of their readings. I have a background in physics so I have some experience with instrumentation.  This situation continued for perhaps 6 hours, then the fever slowly went down and the %SpO2 increased to 90 ? 91, which was ?manageable?, then slowly higher. It is still lower than it had been, but feels normal enough.    Since this dramatic drop in %SpO2 seemed a part of COVID-19 symptoms, I thought this might be significant, and that is why I am reporting it.
HISTORY: Low level of asthma.  I've have never had an "event".

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday, February 19, 2021- Woke up to approximately one inch rash at Moderna injection site on upper left arm. On Monday, Feb 22- primary doctor had never heard of Covid arm and prescribed Amoxicillin for Cellulitis.  On Tuesday, Feb 23- Went to Dermatologist who confirmed Covid arm and prescribed Triamcinolone Cream.  Wednesday morning at 3am- rash on arm improved but developed severe burning, itching, pain swelling, throughout my entire body. All the skin throughout my body was red, especially the joints.  I was developing sores in my mouth.   Felt like third degree burn all over my skin.  I returned to doctors office who advised was having a severe delayed allergic reaction to Moderna vaccine.  She also advised that I had sores in my mouth and my tongue was swollen and I could get anaphylactic and to go to the emergency room immediately if I could not breathe.  She prescribed Zyrtec and 8 days of Prednisone.
LAB_DATA: She did full CBC bloodwork and CRP and Erythrocyte bloodwork which all came back normal.

Later, after 9:00 a.m., there was warmth and itching on my lower back. At 9:45 a.m. I felt flushing in my thighs and lower legs. At 10:00 a.m. there was an actual red rash on my chest and stomach. This all seems unusual for one week after the CoVID-19 shot.     2/27/21 (Sat.) ? Starting at 9:50 a.m. (30 minutes after taking 500 mg. of Niacin, which usually results in immediate flushing of my face, for only a few minutes at most), I had flushing and itching, and a slight rash, on my upper chest and upper back. After a few minutes the flushing and itching spread to my lower back, and my upper arms; my upper arms had a noticeable rash, which then spread down to my hands. In the next few minutes the flushing, itching and rash extended to my upper inner thighs and lower back (although I am only assuming, based on the feeling of flushing and itching, that my lower back had a rash, since I couldn?t see there). Over the next several minutes the itching and rash extended to the front and side of my thighs, down to my knees. The rash then extended, to a lesser extent, down to my ankles. As of 10:50 a.m. I still have this flushing, itching and/or rash in all the places mentioned, although it has started to decrease. This was mostly gone by 12:00 p.m. Other than 4 days ago, I don?t think I have previously experienced this generalized reaction in my 73 years.

S---Ambulance is stationed at a Covid19 vaccination clinic. A female employee of the site host was seen by EMS monitoring the clinic who appeared to be in distress. The monitor approached her, discovered she had been given a vaccination shot approximately one hour prior. The monitor called the ambulance crew over to evaluate the woman. She states she doesn't feel well. Her pulse is rapid (130 bpm). She is assisted inside where vitals are taken. BP is 140/113, HR 113, RR 30, O2 stat 98% on room air. Patient speech demonstrates 3-word dyspnea. Her hands are blue. Patient consents to a more thorough exam in ambulance; stretcher is brought to her side, she is placed Fowlers, strapped with 5-point restraints, and moved to ambulance for transport to hospital for further evaluation. O--Cardiac monitor is attached to patient. A normal sinus rhythm with no ectopy is shown. Lung sounds clear equal. No evidence of trauma. Patient states she is nauseous. Vitals are elsewhere in this report. Other than conditions described, exam is unremarkable. A--Possible reaction to C19 vaccine. Possible anxiety. P--Transport to hospital. IV attempted, no success. 4.0 mg. ondansetron ODT is given to good effect. Trip uneventful. Arrival at hospital, patient is taken to Room 3. Patient looks much better, states she doesn't want to be admitted to ER. and signs (attached) refusal of screening exam at the ER. Patient is given a courtesy return ride with ambulance.

I felt a little lightheaded after the first shot on 1/28/21, they had me stay an additional 15" and I felt ok. After the 2nd shot on 2/25, I immediately felt a little lightheaded, sat for 15", when I stood up to leave I felt lightheaded and had to sit down. The staff member got me a cup of juice and some water. I stayed for another 15", I felt better, a little kind of "flighty" feeling but not like I did when I had to sit. I went home and did ok. I dont think i drank enough fluids that evening. That night around midnight I had chills and could not sleep, muscle aches, headache. Around 8 am when I woke up to go to the bathroom, I felt so lightheaded that I had to lay back down, my temp was 100.4. I drank some water. I got back up to take tylenol and get more to drink. I still felt lightheaded and fatigue, temp was down to 99.6. I drank 3 bottles of water and a gatorade before I needed to urinate. I dont know if the lightheaded feelings were a drop in blood pressure and the more intense lightheadedness the next day after the 2nd shot was a presyncopal episode. I continued to nap and drink fluids until about 2p when I woke up I no longer felt lightheaded and the fatigue was getting better. I still had a headache til that night. I did call Occupational Health to go over my symptoms, they told me to push fluids and rest.  Today I emailed my doctor, PCP to go over things and see if he thinks this was a reaction to the vaccine vs not drinking enough the night before, I am leaning toward a reaction since it made me feel weird right after the shot for both times. As of Saturday 2/27 AM I am feeling more like myself, still drinking alot and resting though.
LAB_DATA: Nothing. I stayed home and drank alot of fluids and rested. I'm a nurse. I should have called my doctors office that day but I was so fatigued and kind of out of it.

Patient received the COVID19 vaccine at 12:00 PM.  She waited her requisite 15 observation window, at which point she reported that she was feeling well.  At 1:00 PM, patient returned to the pharmacy to speak with the pharmacy staff.  She stated that she was driving home with her daughter in the car, talking to her daughter, and that's when her daughter noticed that the patient's tongue appeared green.  We asked the patient to show us her tongue, and the flat surface of her tongue had a bright green color to it.  She stated that she had not eaten or drunk anything since her vaccine nor did she take any other medications since the vaccine.  She did not report any issues with breathing, swelling, or other signs and symptoms of an allergic reaction.  Patient was advised to monitor herself and given the option to stay at the pharmacy for us to observe.  She chose to go home, at which point we recommended she have Benadryl on hand just in case she does develop an allergic reaction.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 4 hours after the vaccine, I experienced sudden nausea and abdominal pain. The symptoms lasted for about a week. They were intermittent at first. The first two subsided, but the third episode on 02/16/21 was more pronounced. I felt generally unwell, like something was really wrong. I first thought it was a normal immune response or side effect. But the nausea and abdominal pain had grown worse. On 02/16/2021 I went to the ER, where a CT Scan showed I had Epiploic Appendagitis. I suspect the inflammation or a sudden ischemic event after my vaccine had caused this. I had absolutely no such symptoms prior to the vaccine, but the nausea came on exactly 4 hours after my first dose like a switch had been turned on.    In addition to the above, I experience facial flushing on the left side of my face for about 7 days after the vaccine. My forehead and right side of my face would read a normal temperature, but my left cheek averaged 101 degrees. The flushing would come on suddenly, often in the evening. I also had heart palpitations.   Other symptoms: I had the typical sore left arm for a few days. I developed joint pain on my left side, including my arm and my jaw. In general, I feel like I had a pronounced inflammatory response.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: In addition to recognized side effects, approximately 24 hours after injection, I experienced sudden-onset severe pain in my right shoulder that traveled through my biceps and into my elbow. On a scale of 1-10, I?d rate the severity as a 10. This lasted approximately 15 minutes.   Over the ensuing 5 days I had noticeable but tolerable intermittent right arm pain. Then beginning on the 10th day following injection, I experienced sudden and severe right shoulder pain that traveled down my biceps into my elbow again. I'd rate the pain at a 9 on the same scale. This time however, the pain started around 11 pm and did not subside. I tried sleeping but couldn?t. I got up and spent the rest of the night holding my arm to immobilize it, however that did nothing to stop the pain. It was about 5 am when I finally took 50 mg diclofenac and in about 2 hours the pain subsided to a tolerable 4 on the same pain scale.   As the day wore on, the pain increased again to a level 9 without medication so I continued with 50 mg diclofenac every 8 hours over the following 4 days and knocked it back to a level 3. This pain has occurred in my right shoulder, biceps, elbow, forearm and even my fingers and intensifies toward evening. I have been able to tolerate the pain without medication at about a level 3 for the past 2 days. However, I take a 50 mg tab of diclofenac an hour or 2 before bed as the pain intensifies toward evening. This has allowed me to sleep through the night.   In addition to the arm pain I developed muscle weakness in my right biceps about 3 days ago and am unable to lift my right arm above my head. The pain is not what prevents the movement. It?s as though my arm is not receiving the nerve impulse to move. Taking all of this together, I?d say that immunization appears to have triggered Parsonage Turner Syndrome. As I understand this immune-mediated syndrome, several events can trigger it, including immunization. I experienced this phenomenon one other time, approximately 2 years ago but did not correlate it to a vaccination at the time. This time it?s too apparent. I wonder how many other reports you?ve received that are like this and whether the vaccines will trigger the same reactions. I also wonder now whether I should receive a Moderna ?booster? if needed in the near to long term. I have no interest in going through this event a
HISTORY: Asthma (exercise and cold weather induced) GRD
