SYMPTOM_TEXT: According to staff....Recipient received the above vaccination and went to sit for 30 minutes.  He had already explained to the staff that he had had previous reactions to bee stings that required epinephrine so the nurse practitioner had  instructed him that he was to wait for 30 minutes vs the usual 15 minutes.  It is unclear exactly how many minutes into the post-vaccination period passed before he began to report numbness around his lips.  The nurse practitioner then indicated he began a "rash" on the back of his neck.  The recipient reported that this was feeling very much like his previous allergic reactions.  They took his BP and it was reported to be around 180/100 at that time.   He did not report feeling SOB but reported his throat felt like it had in previous allergic reactions.  Recipient remained alert and oriented the entire time.  It was decided by the two nurse practitioners on site that he be given the epinephrine and Benadryl IM.  His BP remained elevated and then, following the epinephrine, he became very shaky and a bit foggy. 911 was then notified for further assistance from the EMT's and possible evaluation at the local hospital which was about 5 minutes away.  Paramedics evaluated the recipient and agreed that evaluation at the hospital would be warranted.  He never lost consciousness or required oxygen or other assistance. He was able to place himself on the gurney and was speaking with his wife (that was present)as he was taken out the door.  The transfer was done out of an abundance of caution. We do not know if the hospital kept him following the incident.

My heart rate was up to 150bpm at its highest while at rest. I took 800mg ibuprofen which seemed to help.  The next day I was very fatigued and nauseated. I started to have some gum soreness as well. The next day (2/21) I felt much better, but my lips felt very chapped along with some gum pain. As the days went on, the inside of my lips against my gums and teeth felt very raw and painful, and my lips became extremely chapped, while the corners of my mouth were cracked and painful as well.  On or around 2/24, I began to have some very sore spots on my soft palate, inner lips, and inside of my cheeks. They mostly became small white sores, except for my lips, which became very red with tiny blood spots just under the skin.  As of today (2/27), I still have sore gums, small sores on the inside of my mouth, several under my tongue, and the red sore spots on the inside of my lips.  It isn't life-threatening, but it is very uncomfortable, and makes eating and drinking painful. I don't feel the need to go to an ED or urgent care at this time, but will try to make an appointment with a GP as soon as I can.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am not 100% certain of this event being related to the vaccination with the Moderna COVID19 shot or not.  However, in the interest of completeness and for investigative purposes, I am reporting to you the event in relation to the vaccination as the patient reported to me.  She received the vaccination on 2/14/2021 and became very confused.  She had significant left arm swelling much worse than when she had her first vaccination.  Her husband brought her to the emergency room and she was eventually discharged, but she went on to develop significant hypertension and she reported that her blood pressures were normal prior to the vaccination.  She had an emergency room visit in which her systolic pressures were well above 240.  She revisited the emergency room and had elevated blood pressures of 240 and was diagnosed with hypertensive encephalopathy and later found to have posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome or PRES.  We have started the patient on medications, and started laboratory work-up for secondary hypertension and her blood pressures have improved with treatment.  We discussed the case with the neurologist, who suggested that we repeat MRI scan to make sure that her punctate lesions noted on MRI on this admission on 2/25/2021, have resolved.  It was advised that if they had not resolved that we should call neurology again.  Hypertensive encephalopathy is rare and press syndrome as a result is also rare.  It is for this reason that I am reporting this event as again, I am not trying to mislead anyone or distort information, but should this be an adverse effect of the vaccine I wanted to make sure that this was reported as the patient's history prior to the vaccination and developing this complication post vaccination are temporally related at a minimum.  The patient is a known smoker but quit on the 14th of this month.
LAB_DATA: Patient has an MRI scan that shows punctate lesions in an atypical distribution in the parietal and frontal lobes.  When I discussed with the neurologist the results of this finding, he suggested that its consistent with PRES syndrome.  The MRI is to be repeated.  Thus far CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis was negative, stress test, Lexiscan, was negative and normal.  Preliminary echocardiogram report without the dictated report is normal with normal valve function and a normal ejection fraction.  Her systolic blood pressures are now ranging fairly consistently in the 140s.  Blood pressure is 1 15-1 40 recently.  Laboratory work-up for secondary hypertension is all pending.

chest pain & weakness Narrative:  Pt received his covid vaccine dose #1 on 1/29/2021. On 1/30/2021 he experienced a fever, chest pains and weakness. Pt reported this at his appointment to receive his 2nd dose of covid vaccine on 2/26/2021. Nurse administering vaccine informed pharmacist pt reported he was still feeling weak from the first vaccine dose, so weak he could not perform ADLs without assistance. Pharmacist recommended pt be sent to the ER evaluation, possibly pt has an illness unrelated to the vaccine and another dose may cause worsening of symptoms. Upon further investigation pt was seen at outside hospital ER on day after his dose #1 covid vaccine for chest pain, pleural effusion and weakness and low grade fever. Pt was evaluated and transferred to ER dept. ER gave him morphine iv, magnesium iv, & furosemide 40mg iv. Pt was admitted on 01/31/2021. Pt evaluated by cardiology, internal medicine & given a course of antibiotics. Pt was diagnosed with Chronic Right side pleural effusion, POA. Pt was discharged on 2/3/2021 with the following medication discharge instructions: "SUMMARY OF MEDICATION CHANGES NEW meds: -Start cefdinir 300mg by mouth twice a day for infection - take first dose evening of 2/3/2021 and last dose evening of 2/4/2021 - Start ferrous sulfate (iron) 325mg by mouth every other day - Start pantoprazole 40mg by mouth daily 30 to 60 minutes before breakfast CHANGED meds: -Metoprolol succinate 50mg by mouth daily changed to metoprolol tartrate 12.5mg (=1/2 25mg tablet) by mouth twice a day STOPPED meds: -Stop taking lisinopril until follow-up with your primary care provider -Stop taking omeprazole Of note pt's medical history includes the following comorbidities: *Gastroesophageal reflux disease *Coronary arteriosclerosis *Carotid atherosclerosis *Carcinoma of colon * Colostomy present *Hyperbilirubinemia On 2/26/2021 vaccine dose #2 was held. Pt was encouraged by nurse to follow up with PCP or to report to ER for further evaluation. Pt was given phone # to reschedule dose#2 if appropriate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient Statement:  No symptoms until the following morning at about 7:30am when I noticed mild discomfort and subsequently measured my heart rate via iWatch.  The results indicated tachycarida, with rates raning from about 54 to 173 BPM,  The rate would rise slowly to different peaks, remaining at that level for 1 to 3 mins, then return slowly to normal, the periods of change being in the 1 to 3 minute range.  When running a ECG via my iWatch the Sinus Rhythm appeared abnormal only in period, showing changing rates mirroring what my BPM showed.  The distress was more psychological than physiological, feeling about the same as when our grade school PE teacher would make us run every day.  I hated running, as the breathing burned my lungs and gave me discomfort, but I'm sure it was the same for all of us.  I have no allergies, have never had Influenza, was never absent a single day from school for sickness from Kindergarten all the way through 4 years of college.  I had a cardio work-up a few years ago that showed nothing abnormal, and a health screening about 2 years ago for deep vein and extremity circulation without nominal results.  I've been nearly vegan for several years, and have lost around 30 lbs within the last year, approaching a BMI withing normal range.  I do have a slightly elevated BP, but that is reducing with weight loss.  I have had kidney stones since about 1996, but they tend to pass withing a few hours.  Nothing else to report.
OTHER_MEDS: Salicylic Acid 325mg every 3 days or so

Injection on  Wednesday at 3 PM. No immediate reaction. However, a few hours after the shot my left arm (at the injection site) was sore and swollen.  That evening it was painful and disrupted my sleep. The next morning (Thursday) I was somewhat feverish. By the mid-morning my fever was up to 100.4, and by the late afternoon it was up to 101.4. I felt exhausted -- too exhausted to even write an email. I had chills, backache,  and slept nearly the entire day (~8 hours). Based on this, I would call this day a 4 in terms of severity.   The next day (Friday), my fever had declined to 100.2 but was still elevated, but now I had a backache (lower back), and I was still weak. However, I could get out of bed for about 10 minutes without too much difficulty. I slept for about 5 hours during the day. This may also qualify as a 4.  On Saturday, my fever had declined further to 99.4, and my energy level was somewhat better.  Even so, most of the day was spent in bed, but I slept less during the day than on the previous days (about 3 hours). The main thing that was a problem on Saturday besides being weak was a headache. This is a strange thing because I rarely have had headaches in my life.  This is a pounding in the front of my head, only occurring when going from an upright position into a seated or supine position. Most of the headache disappears in about 30 seconds.  Overall I would say Saturday was a 3 in terms of severity. Today (Sunday) my temperature seems to be normal (98.6) -- though this is a full degree above what is normal for me. However, the headache has become worse -- it was hurting me while sleeping, and woke me up from the discomfort.  I still have the backache, and I am still weak. It's only 6 AM here so I cannot comment on how the rest of the day will go.
The nausea and fatigue started around 11 AM on Friday, and I've still got the nausea. I also threw up Sunday around 6 AM

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 10 seconds I began to feel that something was wrong.   A full body response of a swirling congestion, extreme weakness. very blurry vision and couldn't think straight.  I had trouble walking to recovery room, felt nauseous and weak and had a very fast heartrate.  I had to stay in private recovery room for 45 min.  I was still very ill and nervous at this point.   I left with a family member and asked to be driven to the nearby hospital emergency room.  For a precaution .  We parked across from ER entrance for another 1 hour till I slowly regained strength to 50% normalcy.  I went home afterwards and had to go to bed. I was unable to drive my own vehicle home.  Day 2, still feel weak, shaky and not normal.  I consider this a serious adverse reaction that did not receive medical intervention but will prevent me from getting the second Pfizer shot.  After 5 hours post injection I felt 60% normal .  Day 2, 70 per cent normal.   The vaccination facility was not able to do blood pressure monitoring ( which is a problem for anyone experiencing reactions.)  They said their protocol was to call 911/ambulance.   My blood pressure was checked by a certified PA with professional equipment at the 3 hour post injection time and the diastolic pressure was still below 50.  And heart rate above normal.  Still weak and nauseous.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Night of 2nd vaccine woke up with a high fever, and severe headache. Fever lasted 36 hours and peaked at 104.8 (with Tylenol).  Fever was over 103 degrees for majority of 24 hour period. Fever went away after 36 hours.  However, headaches have continued constantly (17 days and counting).    Went to the Dr. on 2/19/21.  They wanted an CT Scan of head and sinuses.  Dr. Prescribed cefuroxime 250 MG tablet in case of sinus infection and ibuprofen 800 MG tablets.  Insurance did not approve a STAT CT Scan, so Dr. told me to go to the ER if headache persisted.  Went to the ER on  2/23/21.  Dr's indicated Blood pressure was very high (180/120).  I do not have a history of high blood pressure.  They did a CT scan (normal) EKG (normal), and blood work.  They inserted an IV with migraine cocktail to alleviate headache.  Unfortunately no change.  While in the ER they gave me:  - Sodium Chloride - Tylenol - Metoclopramide (injection) - DiphenhydrAMINE (Benedryl) (injection) - Dexamethsone  - Ketorolac (Toradol)  They prescribed methylprednisolone (steroid).  Went back to primary doctor on 2/25.  Blood pressure remains high (average 158/112 throughout the day), headaches continue (constant).  They did more blood work, urine sample, and another EKG.   They also ordered a STRESS ECHOCARDIOGRAM.  The prescribed lisinopril 10 MG tablet for blood pressure.
LAB_DATA: Most lab results have been normal with the exception of:  2/23 - WBC wnl with elevated myelocyte % (result 3 - normal 0) and myelocyte (result .3 - lab ref range - 0.0 10*3/uL) on 2/25 - WBC count was elevated.  However, WBC was in typical range on 2/23.  They believe the steroids could be contributing to the elevation.
OTHER_MEDS: escitalopram 10 MG tablet finasteride 1 MG tablet Flonase Vitamin D Multi Vitamin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The night after the shot I became ill with mild flulike symptoms: headache, fever of 101, aches, chills. This seemed fully within what I had expected and been told might happen, but as these symptoms eased up over the next 48 hours, I experienced, and continue to experience, a weird neurological paresthesia-type symptom where it feels as though my skin is covered in some kind of cold minty lotion. (Not the same as chills, though it sounds like it, I realize.) Mostly on my upper back, but also at the injection site, and sometimes other places too. Not painful, just distracting and  kind of worrying. Not anything I have ever experienced before, and not related to any sort of external variable. I consulted with both a doctor and my brother and his wife (both doctors) by telephone. Everyone has advised a wait and see approach, but my brother (an epidemiologist) recommended that I report this as an adverse event.
HISTORY: Some hay fever / asthma Migraine headaches

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Woke up at my usual time the day after vaccine. Felt a little warm but not feverish and did not take my temperature. Shaking was only seconds long.  Then I must have fainted as I awoke (quickly) on the floor  alongside the cupboards and sliding glass door.  I laid there conscious about 15 minutes till I felt confident I could get up on my own. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 8 days post vaccine 2/25, my arm started to hurt again in late afternoon early evening, as it did the first 24-48 hours of the injection date. By the time I went to sleep, it was uncomfortable to sleep on that side, and it started to itch a bit. The next day (2/26, day 8 post injection) I had flu-like symptoms - very bad headache, fatigue, body aches, and slightly elevated temp (99.4-99.9) - general malaise. I took some Advil in the evening to help with the headache and general malaise and it worked. My arm still hurt and was itchy on and off. By Saturday (2/27, day 9) the flu like symptoms were mostly gone (yay), but I woke up with  a large, red, slightly raised bump and was itchy on and off at the injection site. It was BRIGHT RED and HOT to the touch. Today, day 10, it is still red but a much more dull red, and not as hot to touch, and doesn't hurt as much. So I think it's clearing up! I should note that I once had a very similar reaction to a flu shot, about 5 years ago, and thus continue to get my  flu shot in the doctor's office just to be safe, and I sit for 15 minutes to ensure I don't get a reaction. I had a red, warm, itchy welt around the injection site. The reaction I had with my flu shot was also several days after the injection, but not as many as the Moderna shot.  I have read that this is called "Covid arm" and a known reaction which is comforting, but I wanted to be sure to report it BECAUSE SCIENCE is important. I also understand this should not deter me from getting my second dose, but I am curious to know if I should expect the same reaction? The article I read suggested getting the second dose in the OPPOSITE arm, which would be my dominant arm (I am a lefty.) I am hoping someone from VAERS can advise me if I should switch arms, or even delay my vaccine. Right now, dose two is scheduled for 3/17, 4 weeks after my first dose. Thank you.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu shot
ALLERGIES: I have had a similar reaction with a flu shot, to the one I received with this vaccine
